# Ariadne

Before you write or change behavior, you **must** follow the workflow and the **content contract** below. The registry is a **map to the real source of truth** in the repo, not a second full copy of implementations.

## Workflow (always)

1. **Search** `.ariadne/registry/*.md` (e.g. codebase / semantic search) before adding parallel APIs.
2. **Reuse** registered exports when they fit. If an entry lists `error_codes` or `dependencies` with real values, respect them. If a field is **`n/a` or empty**, there is no extra contract in the file—treat the **TypeScript source** in the path under **Source** as the authority; update the entry after meaningful changes.
3. **No duplicate** bottom-layer APIs: do not re-implement what is already covered by a registry entry and its source file.
4. **Missing entry**: tell the user no suitable component was found and suggest extending the registry and source.
5. **Keep the registry current**: after you **Write** a registry-eligible file, the optional Cursor **`postToolUse` hook** from `ariadne init` will inject a reminder as **`additional_context`**: you must **re-read** the file, **author a 1–3 sentence English Purpose** (description) for what changed, then run `ariadne update <path> "<purpose or rely on JSDoc>"` yourself. The hook does **not** run `ariadne` headlessly; it nudges you to produce a good **desc** before/while updating. If the hook is off, run `update` the same way manually.

## Ariadne registry content contract

These rules keep entries **small, stable, and aligned** with what the CLI and humans maintain.

| Topic | Rule |
|--------|------|
| **Granularity** | Prefer **one resolvable `export` symbol (value, type, or re-export) → one** `.md` under `.ariadne/registry/`, per the CLI. Do not put half a file’s narrative in a single “mega” entry. |
| **Purpose** | **1–3 short sentences** (English unless the project standard says otherwise). State *what* and *when* to use it, not a full design essay. The CLI can fill this from a passed purpose or the first JSDoc paragraph. |
| **Code Signature** | **Contract only**: signature / parameters / return, **not** a copy of 20+ lines of loop/body. The canonical implementation stays in the **source file** listed as **Source**. If you need a line range, add a one-line “see `path#L`” in Purpose or a future note—do not mirror full algorithms here. |
| **Contract (import / name / domain)** | For noisy signatures (e.g. React props objects, big inline types), the generator adds a **Contract** section. Fill **how to import or call**, **input value domain** (types, allowed values, invariants), and **output/return domain**; leave `n/a` only while unknown. This is the precision you want on top of the raw `Code Signature` block. |
| **error codes & reasons** | The body section under that heading (and front matter `error_codes`) is for **code or category → reason** when the API is stable. Replace `n/a` when you document real behavior. |
| **Freshness** | The registry is for **orientation, boundaries, and link-out**; it is **not** a second source tree. If an entry and its source disagree, **fix the entry** (or the code) in the same change. |
| **error_codes** | Present in front matter. **`n/a`** = no error-code list is asserted for this entry yet. Fill when your API has stable error semantics. |
| **dependencies** | Present in front matter. **`n/a`** = not specified. When order matters, write a one-line call/composition order (e.g. “use `foo` then `bar`”); keep it under one line if possible. |

**`ariadne sync` vs. real “semantic” updates:** `sync` batch-rebuilds every matched file with **JSDoc or a placeholder** only. It is **not** a substitute for having the **agent read the code and author Purpose**; use **`ariadne update <file> "…" after reading`**, or add JSDoc then re-`update`. Reserve `sync` for cold start / CI skeletons / intentional bulk re-index, then refine entries.

**One-shot full check:** run `ariadne audit` in the project root. It prints a table of every export + whether the registry file exists and whether the Purpose is still a placeholder, plus a **copy-paste block** for the agent to triage the whole set in one session (the CLI does not call an LLM itself).

**Quality bar for agents and humans:** avoid duplicating another entry’s **Purpose** text; avoid pasting the same long paragraph for unrelated symbols. If you tighten types in source, re-run `update` for that file (or `sync` only when you accept placeholder-quality text and will fix Purposes afterward).
